Marketing

Profile: Spreading the Word 

Read preview








                            Magazine article
                        
Marketing

Profile: Spreading the Word 

Read preview




Article excerpt

  Sophie Gasperment Managing director, consumer and professional products division, L'Oreal UK & Ireland.    Sometimes life changes because you happen to be in a certain place at a certain time. That is certainly the case for L'Oreal UK's Sophie Gasperment. The 41-year-old got her first job at the company 20 years ago by chance.    'I had lots of interviews lined up during the university 'milk round' and I was very early for my first interview, for a management consultancy, and they were very late. I had two hours (to kill) and I didn't know what to do. I opened the next door and L'Oreal was doing presentations (to graduates),' Gasperment recalls.    'I just loved the way they were talking about the company - full of passion, energy and decisiveness,' she says. 'So, I listened to the presentation, got an interview at 2pm and by 5pm they had offered me a job.'    Her decisiveness is reflected in all areas of L'Oreal's business. 'You have to be really quick because this industry is very fast-paced,' she notes.    Paris-born and bred, Gasperment moved to London six years ago with her husband and children, then aged six and eight. Since then, the family has embraced the British way of life - even giving the most recent addition to the family, a seven month old daughter, the very English name of Emma - and Gasperment feels fully settled in London. 'I don't plan to move on,' she says.    In her spare time she enjoys taking the family to concerts and music festivals. 'Music in London is so much more accessible than in Paris,' she says. 'It's more relaxed and is of a fantastic quality. Here, you go to a concert because you like music and you are passionate about it.    It is not highbrow like it is in France, or some sort of social display.'    Gasperment also enjoys picking up English colloquialisms and has a small book in which she notes any she finds particularly amusing - favourite entries include 'a bird in the hand is worth two in the bush' and 'not counting your chickens before they are hatched'.    She cites her balance of work and family life as one of her biggest achievements.    'I have been able to thrive professionally and have my family and enjoy seeing them develop,' she says. Her secret may be her insistence that, whatever the day has in store, she sits down for 'a very early breakfast' with her children.    Her favourite part of her job is team-building. … 






